  "prompt": "Is power steering fluid the same as brake fluid?",
  "response": "No, power steering fluid and brake fluid are **not** the same thing and should **never** be used interchangeably. They are specifically formulated for their respective systems and have different properties:\n\n*   **Power Steering Fluid:** Primarily designed to transmit hydraulic pressure to assist in steering. It often contains additives to lubricate the power steering pump and other components.\n\n*   **Brake Fluid:** Designed to transmit hydraulic pressure from the brake pedal to the brakes. It must withstand very high temperatures without boiling (which would create air bubbles and lead to brake failure) and must not compress under pressure. It also needs to protect the brake system from corrosion.\n\n**Using the wrong fluid can lead to serious problems:**\n\n*   **Putting power steering fluid in the brake system:** This can cause seals and rubber components to swell and fail, leading to brake failure.\n*   **Putting brake fluid in the power steering system:** This can damage the power steering pump and other components, leading to steering failure.\n\n**In short: Always use the correct fluid specified for each system.**\n\nIf you're unsure which fluid to use, consult your vehicle's owner's manual or a qualified mechanic.\n",
